00:00:21.012 --> 00:00:22.095
PROFESSOR: Good afternoon.

00:00:27.390 --> 00:00:32.180
We continue our discussion
of quantum states of light.

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:36.210
We talked at length
about coherent state,

00:00:36.210 --> 00:00:39.720
and when you talk about
quantum states of light,

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:41.400
each mode of the
electromagnetic field

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:43.040
is an harmonic oscillator.

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:46.690
We also encountered,
naturally, the number states.

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:51.243
And we realized--
yesterday, actually,

00:00:51.243 --> 00:00:54.140
in the last class-- that
those number states have

00:00:54.140 --> 00:00:56.190
non-classical properties.

00:00:56.190 --> 00:00:59.490
For instance, they have a g2
function, the second order

00:00:59.490 --> 00:01:01.790
correlation function,
which is smaller

00:01:01.790 --> 00:01:05.230
than 1, which is impossible
for classic light,

00:01:05.230 --> 00:01:08.670
as you're proving in one of
your homework assignment.

00:01:08.670 --> 00:01:12.580
So at that point, we have
encountered coherent states,

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:15.830
which are as close as
possible to classical states.

00:01:15.830 --> 00:01:19.360
And we have found the number
states as non-classical states.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:22.950
Well, are there other
interesting states?

00:01:22.950 --> 00:01:26.450
I wouldn't ask you this question
if the answer would not be yes,

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:28.690
and this is what we
want to discuss today.

00:01:28.690 --> 00:01:32.420
We want to talk about
non-classical states of light,

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:36.710
which we can engineer,
actually, in the laboratory,

00:01:36.710 --> 00:01:38.970
by sending laser light
through nonlinear crystals.

00:01:45.130 --> 00:01:51.030
Those go by the name,
squeezed states.

00:01:51.030 --> 00:01:57.540
Just to give you
the cartoon picture,

00:01:57.540 --> 00:02:02.350
in our two-dimensional diagram,
with the quasi-probabilities,

00:02:02.350 --> 00:02:10.990
we have coherent
states, where the area

00:02:10.990 --> 00:02:14.640
of this disk, delta x
delta p, is h-bar over two.

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:17.970
It's uncertainty limited.

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:22.140
What we can do we now, is--
we cannot go beyond this.

00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:25.750
This is the fundamental
limit of quantum physics.

00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:31.390
However, we can take this
circle and we can squeeze it.

00:02:31.390 --> 00:02:36.090
We can squeeze it
horizontally, we can squeeze it

00:02:36.090 --> 00:02:38.170
into an elongated
vertical shape,

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:41.140
or we can squeeze
it at any angle.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:43.280
That's what we call,
squeezed states.

00:02:51.090 --> 00:02:56.570
And those states have
non-classical properties.

00:02:56.570 --> 00:02:59.125
They are important
for metrology they

00:02:59.125 --> 00:03:01.110
are important for teleportation.

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:02.580
There are lots and
lots of reasons

00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:05.620
why you want to know about them.

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:10.930
But again, as so often, I
feel I cannot convey to you

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:14.670
the excitement of doing
squeezing in the quantum

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:15.460
domain.

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:17.343
And many, many
physicists now, they

00:03:17.343 --> 00:03:20.510
hear about squeezing just
in the quantum domain.

00:03:20.510 --> 00:03:22.810
But I want to start with
classical squeezing.

00:03:28.760 --> 00:03:31.140
I will actually show you
video of an experiment

00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:32.430
on classical squeezing.

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:36.020
You can see squeezing
with your own eyes.

00:03:36.020 --> 00:03:38.760
But this is just sort
of to set the stage,

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:41.860
to also get a feel
of what squeezing is.

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:44.655
And then we'll do quantum
mechanical squeezing.

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:49.280
But maybe-- tongue
in cheek-- I would

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:52.400
say, since classical harmonic
oscillators and quantum

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:54.730
harmonic oscillators
have a lot in common,

00:03:54.730 --> 00:03:57.310
the step from classical
squeezing to quantum

00:03:57.310 --> 00:03:59.520
of mechanical squeezing
is actually rather small.

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:04.420
It's nice to squeeze light.

00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:06.890
It's nice to have those
non-classical states.

00:04:06.890 --> 00:04:09.560
But the question is,
how can you detect it?

00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:13.890
If you can't detect it, you
can't take advantage of it.

00:04:13.890 --> 00:04:16.730
And the detection has
to be face-coherent.

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:18.380
I will tell you what that is.

00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:22.770
And it goes by the name,
homodyne detection.

00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:25.970
And finally, we
can take everything

00:04:25.970 --> 00:04:31.440
we have learned together, and
discuss how, in the laboratory,

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:34.681
teleportation of a
quantum state is done.

00:04:34.681 --> 00:04:37.140
There is a nice
teleportation scheme,

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:39.190
and I want to use
that as an example

00:04:39.190 --> 00:04:41.540
that the language and the
concepts I've introduced

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:43.290
are useful.

00:04:43.290 --> 00:04:45.250
Concepts like,
squeezing operator,

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:49.330
displacement operator--
those methods

00:04:49.330 --> 00:04:54.657
allowing us to, in
a very clear way,

00:04:54.657 --> 00:04:56.490
discuss schemes which
lead to teleportation.

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:01.340
That's the menu for today.

00:05:05.540 --> 00:05:07.645
Let's start with
classical squeezing.

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:30.590
For squeezing, we need
an harmonic oscillator,

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:34.010
means for parabolic potential,
we have potential v of x.

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:44.681
And then we study
the motion of-- that

00:05:44.681 --> 00:05:47.910
should be x squared-- the
motion of a particle in there.

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:49.800
Before I even get
started any equation,

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:53.660
let me explain what the effect
of squeezing will be about.

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:55.560
If you have an
harmonic oscillator,

00:05:55.560 --> 00:05:59.910
you have, actually, the
motion of a pendulum.

00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:03.240
It has two quadrature
components, the cosine motion

00:06:03.240 --> 00:06:04.430
and the sine motion.

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:07.470
And they are 90
degrees out of phase.

00:06:07.470 --> 00:06:10.780
What happens now is,
if you parametrically

00:06:10.780 --> 00:06:13.590
drive the harmonic
oscillator-- you modulate

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:15.930
the harmonic oscillator
potential-- it's to omega.

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:22.390
I will show you mathematically,
it's very, very easy to show,

00:06:22.390 --> 00:06:25.460
that depending on the
phase of the drive,

00:06:25.460 --> 00:06:29.720
you will actually exponentially
amplify the sine motion,

00:06:29.720 --> 00:06:31.900
and exponentially damp
the cosine motion.

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:34.030
Or if you change, vice versa.

00:06:34.030 --> 00:06:39.290
So by driving the system, you
can amplify one quadrature

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:45.490
component, and exponentially
die out the other quadrature

00:06:45.490 --> 00:06:46.709
component.

00:06:46.709 --> 00:06:48.375
And that is called,
classical squeezing.

00:06:54.010 --> 00:06:55.640
Let's do the math.

00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:56.680
It's very simple.

00:06:59.870 --> 00:07:11.830
Our equation of motion
has the two solutions

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:13.940
I've just mentioned.

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:19.780
It has a solution
with cosine omega 0,

00:07:19.780 --> 00:07:21.950
and one with sine omega 0 t.

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:28.300
And we have two coefficients.

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:30.030
The cosine is called, c.

00:07:30.030 --> 00:07:31.830
The sine coefficient
is called, s.

00:07:41.550 --> 00:07:45.740
I have to call it c 0, because
I want to call that c and s.

00:07:49.070 --> 00:08:02.610
So what we have here is, we have
the two quadrature components

00:08:02.610 --> 00:08:06.770
of the motion in an
harmonic oscillator.

00:08:06.770 --> 00:08:10.450
And graphically, we need that
for the electromagnetic field,

00:08:10.450 --> 00:08:11.560
as well.

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:14.210
When we have our two
axes, like, you know,

00:08:14.210 --> 00:08:17.820
the complex plane for the
cosine of probabilities,

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:21.730
I call one the s-axis.

00:08:21.730 --> 00:08:22.630
One is the c-axis.

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:36.710
That's just something
which confuses me.

00:08:40.350 --> 00:08:51.720
If you have only one--
just give me one second.

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:54.220
Cosine-- Yeah.

00:08:57.070 --> 00:09:03.820
If you have only cosine
motion, the s component is 0,

00:09:03.820 --> 00:09:07.560
and the harmonic oscillator
would just oscillate here.

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:10.700
If you have only
a sine component,

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:12.085
you stay on the x-axis.

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:21.550
And now, if you have an equal
amount of cosine and sine,

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:27.120
then you can describe the
trajectory to go in a circle.

00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:30.220
OK.

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:33.630
This is just the undriven
harmonic oscillator.

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:36.510
I don't want to dwell
on it any longer.

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:39.370
But what we are
doing now is, we are

00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:41.990
adding a small parametric drive.

00:09:54.280 --> 00:10:01.330
Parametric drive means we
modulate the spring constant,

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:08.090
or we replace the original
harmonic potential,

00:10:08.090 --> 00:10:14.710
which was this, by an
extra modulation term.

00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:17.930
So we have a small
parameter, epsilon.

00:10:17.930 --> 00:10:20.610
And as I pointed
out, the modulation

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:22.450
is at twice the
resonance frequency.

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:28.300
Now we want to solve
the equation of motion

00:10:28.300 --> 00:10:31.320
for the harmonic oscillator,
using this added potential.

00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:51.960
The way how we want to solve
it is, we assume epsilon

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:53.420
is very small.

00:10:53.420 --> 00:10:56.420
So if the pendulum is
swinging with cosine omega t,

00:10:56.420 --> 00:10:58.770
it will take a while
for the epsilon

00:10:58.770 --> 00:11:02.520
term-- for the small term--
to change the motion.

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:05.710
So therefore, we assume
that we can actually

00:11:05.710 --> 00:11:12.550
go back and use our
original solution.

00:11:12.550 --> 00:11:16.386
And assume that
over a short term,

00:11:16.386 --> 00:11:18.010
the epsilon term is
not doing anything.

00:11:18.010 --> 00:11:20.710
So for a short time, it looks
like an harmonic oscillator

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:24.660
with a sine omega 0, and
cosine omega 0 t oscillation.

00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:27.830
But over any longer
period of time,

00:11:27.830 --> 00:11:30.530
the small term will
have an effect.

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:34.560
And therefore, the
coefficients c of t, c, and s

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:37.680
are no longer constant, but
change as a function of time.

00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:57.560
We want to solve, now,
the equation of motion.

00:11:57.560 --> 00:12:07.440
That means we use this,
here, as our ansatz.

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:15.300
And we calculate the
second derivative.

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:23.100
We assume that the coefficients
c and s are changing slowly.

00:12:23.100 --> 00:12:28.130
Therefore, the second derivative
of c and s can be neglected.

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:35.370
By taking the derivative
of the second derivative

00:12:35.370 --> 00:12:38.010
of the cosine term
and the sine term,

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:48.950
of course we simply get,
minus omega 0 squared, x of t.

00:12:55.160 --> 00:12:57.510
And now we have the
second-order derivatives.

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:03.070
Since we neglect the
second-order derivative of c

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:05.580
and s, the other
terms we get when

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:08.310
we take the second derivative
is, first derivative

00:13:08.310 --> 00:13:11.230
of c times first
derivative of cosine.

00:13:11.230 --> 00:13:15.190
First derivative of s times
first derivative of sine.

00:13:15.190 --> 00:13:21.460
So we get two more terms,
which are, minus omega 0 c dot,

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:25.880
times sine omega 0 t.

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:36.690
Plus omega 0 s dot,
times cosine omega 0 t.

00:13:36.690 --> 00:13:42.305
This is the second derivative
of our ansatz for x.

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:53.780
This has to be equal
to the force provided

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:55.760
by the potential.

00:13:55.760 --> 00:13:58.440
So taking the potential--

00:14:28.424 --> 00:14:30.340
We need, now, the
derivative of the potential,

00:14:30.340 --> 00:14:33.260
for the potential of
use across this line.

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:35.020
The first part is the
unperturbed harmonic

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:38.460
oscillator, which
gives us simply,

00:14:38.460 --> 00:14:42.430
omega 0 squared times x.

00:14:42.430 --> 00:14:49.670
And the second term, due to
the parametric drive, is 2

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:52.430
sine omega 0 t.

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:56.835
And now, for x,
we use our ansatz

00:14:56.835 --> 00:15:01.640
for x, which is the
slowly-changing amplitude c

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:08.080
times cosine omega 0 t,
plus s times sine omega 0 t.

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:17.130
Those two terms cancel out.

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:30.980
So now we have products
of trig function.

00:15:30.980 --> 00:15:34.140
Sine 2 omega times cosine omega.

00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:38.270
Well, you know if you take the
product of two trig functions,

00:15:38.270 --> 00:15:43.680
it becomes a trig function
of the sum or the difference

00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:45.110
of the argument.

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:49.620
So if you take sine 2 omega
0 times cosine omega 0,

00:15:49.620 --> 00:15:52.520
and we use trigonometric
identities,

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:58.290
we get an oscillation at 3
omega 0, which is 2 plus 1.

00:15:58.290 --> 00:16:00.380
And one at the difference,
which is omega 0.

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:06.500
Let me write down the terms
which are of interest to us.

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:09.220
Namely, the ones at omega 0.

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:15.580
So let me factor out epsilon
omega 0 squared over 2.

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:23.395
Then we have the term c times
sine omega 0 t, plus s times

00:16:23.395 --> 00:16:23.895
cosine.

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:33.640
And then we have
terms at 3 omega

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:37.680
0, which we are
going to neglect.

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:51.530
Now we compare the two
sides of the equations.

00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:53.380
We have sine omega 0 term.

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:56.710
We have cosine omega 0 term.

00:16:56.710 --> 00:16:59.040
And the two sides
of the equations

00:16:59.040 --> 00:17:03.770
are only consistent if the two
coefficients of the sine term,

00:17:03.770 --> 00:17:05.800
and the sine term, are the same.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:08.634
So therefore, we
obtain two equations.

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:15.920
One for c dot, one for s dot.

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:31.480
And these are first-order
differential equations.

00:17:31.480 --> 00:17:34.050
The solution is
clearly an exponential.

00:17:34.050 --> 00:17:37.380
But one has a plus sign,
one has a minus sign.

00:17:37.380 --> 00:17:40.710
So the c component, the
c quadrature component,

00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:43.840
is exponentially amplified
with this time constant.

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:46.990
Whereas the sine component is
exponentially de-amplified.

00:17:55.290 --> 00:17:57.800
This finishes the
mathematical discussion

00:17:57.800 --> 00:17:59.210
of classical squeezing.

00:17:59.210 --> 00:18:08.220
We find that s of t, and c of
t, are exponential functions.

00:18:08.220 --> 00:18:18.290
In one case, it's
exponentially increasing.

00:18:18.290 --> 00:18:25.810
In the other case, it is
exponentially decreasing.

00:18:25.810 --> 00:18:32.940
And that means that, well,
if we go to our diagram,

00:18:32.940 --> 00:18:37.625
here-- and let's assume
we had an arbitrary

00:18:37.625 --> 00:18:40.570
superposition of cosine
and sine amplitude.

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:47.870
This is cosine.

00:18:47.870 --> 00:18:49.210
This is sine.

00:18:49.210 --> 00:18:55.880
We had sort of a
cosine oscillation,

00:18:55.880 --> 00:18:59.500
and a sine oscillation.

00:18:59.500 --> 00:19:08.920
Which means that, as
a phasor, the system

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:11.590
was moving on an ellipse.

00:19:11.590 --> 00:19:15.770
If the sine component is
exponentially de-amplified,

00:19:15.770 --> 00:19:20.190
and the cosine component
is exponentially amplified,

00:19:20.190 --> 00:19:25.110
that means whatever we start
with is squashed horizontally,

00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:26.810
is squashed vertically.

00:19:26.810 --> 00:19:31.480
And is amplified horizontally.

00:19:31.480 --> 00:19:34.809
In the end, it will
become a narrow strip.

00:19:34.809 --> 00:19:36.100
So this is classical squeezing.

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:44.740
You may want to ask, why did
I neglect the 3 omega 0 term.

00:19:44.740 --> 00:19:50.110
Well, I have to, otherwise
I don't have a solution.

00:19:50.110 --> 00:19:53.730
Because I have to be consistent
with my approximations.

00:19:53.730 --> 00:19:57.200
So what I did here
is, I had an equation

00:19:57.200 --> 00:20:03.540
where I have the clear
vision that the solution has

00:20:03.540 --> 00:20:06.300
a slowly varying c
and s coefficient.

00:20:06.300 --> 00:20:08.730
And then I simply use that.

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:13.150
I take the second-order
derivative,

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:15.410
and I have only
Fourier components

00:20:15.410 --> 00:20:17.930
with omega 0, the
sine, and cosine.

00:20:17.930 --> 00:20:22.740
Now I've made an
approximation, here.

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:25.530
For the derivative
of the potential,

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:27.690
the first line is exact.

00:20:27.690 --> 00:20:30.040
But in order to match
the approximation

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:32.450
I've done on the
other side, I can only

00:20:32.450 --> 00:20:37.910
focus on two Fourier components
resonant with omega 0,

00:20:37.910 --> 00:20:39.450
which I have here.

00:20:39.450 --> 00:20:42.140
So in other words,
the 3 omega 0 term

00:20:42.140 --> 00:20:44.900
would lead to additional
accelerations.

00:20:44.900 --> 00:20:49.910
Which I have not included
in the treatment.

00:20:49.910 --> 00:20:51.512
So it's consistent
with the ansatz.

00:20:51.512 --> 00:20:52.970
It's consistent
with the assumption

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:56.490
that we have
resonant oscillations

00:20:56.490 --> 00:20:58.515
with a slowly
changing amplitude.

00:20:58.515 --> 00:21:00.640
There will be a small
[INAUDIBLE] for your omega 0,

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:03.190
but it will be small.

00:21:03.190 --> 00:21:04.340
Any questions about that?

00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:20.580
Let me then show you
an animation of that.

00:21:27.394 --> 00:21:28.060
Classroom files.

00:21:31.184 --> 00:21:31.850
