00:23:33.181 --> 00:23:35.180
He showed what happens
when you have, initially,

00:23:35.180 --> 00:23:37.500
a sine component, and what
happens when you initially

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:40.660
have a cosine component.

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:41.200
OK.

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:44.630
So we know what
classical squeezing is.

00:23:44.630 --> 00:23:49.300
And what we have learned, also--
and this helps me now a lot

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:52.610
to motivate how we squeeze
in quantum mechanics--

00:23:52.610 --> 00:23:56.100
you have realized that what
is really essential here is,

00:23:56.100 --> 00:24:00.610
to drive it to omega 0.

00:24:00.610 --> 00:24:03.020
What we need now to do
squeezing in the quantum domain,

00:24:03.020 --> 00:24:08.210
if we want to squeeze light,
we need something at 2 omega 0.

00:24:08.210 --> 00:24:18.910
So let's now squeeze
quantum mechanically.

00:24:21.780 --> 00:24:22.700
Go back here.

00:24:30.190 --> 00:24:34.315
The second sub-section is
now, squeezed quantum states.

00:24:51.580 --> 00:24:53.330
What we want to
discuss is, we want

00:24:53.330 --> 00:24:58.520
to discuss a quantum
harmonic oscillator.

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:07.940
We want to have some form of
parametric drive at 2 omega 0.

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:13.240
And this will result
in squeezed states.

00:25:19.180 --> 00:25:28.510
Now, what does it require, if
you want to bring in 2 omega 0?

00:25:28.510 --> 00:25:31.480
Well, let's not forget
our harmonic oscillators

00:25:31.480 --> 00:25:34.470
are modes of the
electromagnetic field.

00:25:34.470 --> 00:25:38.440
If you now want to couple a mode
of the electromagnetic field,

00:25:38.440 --> 00:25:44.390
at 2 omega 0, with our
harmonic oscillator at omega 0,

00:25:44.390 --> 00:25:48.070
we need a coupling between
two electromagnetic fields.

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:52.000
So therefore, we need nonlinear
interactions between photons.

00:25:55.150 --> 00:25:56.270
So this was a tautology.

00:25:56.270 --> 00:25:58.347
We need nonlinear
physics, which leads

00:25:58.347 --> 00:25:59.680
to interactions between photons.

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:02.520
Linear physics means,
each harmonic oscillator

00:26:02.520 --> 00:26:03.950
is independent.

00:26:03.950 --> 00:26:07.130
So we need some
nonlinear process

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:14.214
six which will be equivalent
to have interactions

00:26:14.214 --> 00:26:14.880
between photons.

00:26:24.500 --> 00:26:27.900
The device which we
will provide that

00:26:27.900 --> 00:26:30.550
is an optical
parametric oscillator.

00:26:43.690 --> 00:26:47.250
I could spend a long
time explaining to you

00:26:47.250 --> 00:26:49.810
how those nonlinear
crystals work.

00:26:49.810 --> 00:26:53.360
What is the polarization,
what is the polarizability,

00:26:53.360 --> 00:26:56.110
how do you drive it,
what is the nonlinearity.

00:26:56.110 --> 00:27:01.120
But for the discussion
in this class,

00:27:01.120 --> 00:27:03.360
which focuses on
fundamental concepts,

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:06.070
I can actually bypass
it by just saying,

00:27:06.070 --> 00:27:08.910
assume you have a system--
and this is actually

00:27:08.910 --> 00:27:11.010
what the optical
parametric oscillator does,

00:27:11.010 --> 00:27:17.060
is you pump it with
photons at 2 omega 0.

00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:26.240
And then the crystal generates
two photons at omega 0.

00:27:26.240 --> 00:27:30.490
Which of course, is consistent
with energy conservation.

00:27:30.490 --> 00:27:34.250
And if you fulfill some
phase-matching condition,

00:27:34.250 --> 00:27:37.590
it's also consistent with
momentum conservation.

00:27:37.590 --> 00:27:40.100
But I don't want to go into
phase-matching at this point.

00:27:43.290 --> 00:27:48.800
Technically, this is
done as simple as that.

00:27:48.800 --> 00:27:52.120
You have to pick
the right crystal.

00:27:52.120 --> 00:27:55.940
Actually, a crystal which does
mixing between three photon

00:27:55.940 --> 00:27:58.850
fields cannot have
inversion symmetry,

00:27:58.850 --> 00:28:03.160
otherwise this
nonlinear term is 0.

00:28:03.160 --> 00:28:05.110
What you need is
a special crystal.

00:28:05.110 --> 00:28:07.780
KDP is a common choice.

00:28:07.780 --> 00:28:10.415
And this crystal will now
do for us the following.

00:28:13.320 --> 00:28:14.900
You shine in laser light.

00:28:14.900 --> 00:28:19.000
Let's say, at 532
nanometer, a green light.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:31.080
And then this photon breaks up
into two photons of omega 0.

00:28:31.080 --> 00:28:33.490
This is how it's done
in the laboratory.

00:28:33.490 --> 00:28:36.170
The piece of art is, you have
to pick the right crystal.

00:28:36.170 --> 00:28:38.030
It has to be cut
at the right angle.

00:28:38.030 --> 00:28:40.840
You may have to heat
it, and make sure

00:28:40.840 --> 00:28:44.440
that you select the
temperature for which

00:28:44.440 --> 00:28:47.270
some form of resonant condition
is fulfilled, to do that.

00:28:47.270 --> 00:28:48.890
But in essence,
that's what you do.

00:28:48.890 --> 00:28:52.230
One laser beam, put in a
crystal, and then the photon

00:28:52.230 --> 00:28:54.310
is broken into two equal parts.

00:28:54.310 --> 00:28:56.300
And these are our two
photons at omega 0.

00:29:03.300 --> 00:29:03.800
OK.

00:29:07.150 --> 00:29:09.890
I hope you enjoy the
elegance-- we can completely

00:29:09.890 --> 00:29:15.200
bypass all the material physics
by putting operators on it.

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:17.300
We call this mode, b.

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:19.730
And we call this mode, a.

00:29:19.730 --> 00:29:24.840
So the whole parametric process,
the down conversion process

00:29:24.840 --> 00:29:28.230
of one photon into
two, is now described

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:31.310
by the following Hamiltonian.

00:29:31.310 --> 00:29:36.820
We destroy a photon in
mode b, a 2 omega 0.

00:29:36.820 --> 00:29:41.090
And now we create
two photons at omega.

00:29:41.090 --> 00:29:42.760
We destroy a photon
at 2 omega 0,

00:29:42.760 --> 00:29:44.980
create two photons at omega 0.

00:29:44.980 --> 00:29:50.330
And since the Hamiltonian
has to be Hamiltonian,

00:29:50.330 --> 00:29:52.780
the opposite, the
time-reverse process,

00:29:52.780 --> 00:29:54.250
has to be possible, too.

00:29:54.250 --> 00:29:58.350
And that means we destroy
two photons at omega 0,

00:29:58.350 --> 00:30:00.460
and create one
photon at 2 omega 0.

00:30:04.200 --> 00:30:07.100
So now we forget about
nonlinear crystals,

00:30:07.100 --> 00:30:10.220
about non-inversion
symmetry in materials.

00:30:10.220 --> 00:30:12.417
We just take this
Hamiltonian and play with it.

00:30:20.060 --> 00:30:21.720
By simply looking
at the Hamiltonian,

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:23.400
what is the time
evolution of a photon

00:30:23.400 --> 00:30:25.090
field under this Hamiltonian.

00:30:25.090 --> 00:30:27.740
We figure out what happens
when you send light

00:30:27.740 --> 00:30:30.170
through a crystal, and
what is the output.

00:30:30.170 --> 00:30:33.060
And I want to show you now
that the output of that

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:37.380
is squeezed light, which is
exactly what I promised you

00:30:37.380 --> 00:30:39.340
with these quasi-probabilities.

00:30:39.340 --> 00:30:44.270
We have a coherent state,
which is a nice circle.

00:30:44.270 --> 00:30:49.990
We time-evolve the coherent
state, our nice round circle,

00:30:49.990 --> 00:30:51.620
with this Hamiltonian.

00:30:51.620 --> 00:30:52.870
And what we get is an ellipse.

00:30:55.910 --> 00:30:59.190
And if you want intuition,
look at the classical example

00:30:59.190 --> 00:31:01.490
we did before, which
really tells you

00:31:01.490 --> 00:31:05.910
in a more intuitive
way what is happening.

00:31:05.910 --> 00:31:07.190
OK.

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:10.600
We want to make one
simplifying assumption, here.

00:31:10.600 --> 00:31:13.910
And this is that
we pump the crystal

00:31:13.910 --> 00:31:17.320
at 2 omega 0 with a
strong laser beam.

00:31:17.320 --> 00:31:26.450
So we assume that the mode,
b, is a powerful laser beam.

00:31:26.450 --> 00:31:29.440
Or in other words, a
strong coherent state.

00:31:37.330 --> 00:31:42.030
We assume that the mode,
b, is in a coherent state.

00:31:44.600 --> 00:31:46.270
Coherent states
are always labeled

00:31:46.270 --> 00:31:48.940
with a complex parameter,
which I call beta, now.

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:51.150
Well, it's mode b,
therefore I call it, beta.

00:31:51.150 --> 00:31:54.580
For mode a, I've
called it, alpha.

00:31:54.580 --> 00:31:58.610
The coherent state has an
amplitude, which I call,

00:31:58.610 --> 00:31:59.690
r over 2.

00:31:59.690 --> 00:32:00.670
And it has a phase.

00:32:03.550 --> 00:32:11.490
We know, of course, that the
operator, b, acting on beta,

00:32:11.490 --> 00:32:15.450
gives us beta times beta,
because a coherent state is

00:32:15.450 --> 00:32:17.315
an eigenstate of the
annihilation operator.

00:32:21.490 --> 00:32:25.590
But when we look at the
action of the operator b

00:32:25.590 --> 00:32:32.900
plus, the photon
creation operator,

00:32:32.900 --> 00:32:35.080
the coherent state
is not an eigenstate

00:32:35.080 --> 00:32:36.290
of the creation operator.

00:32:36.290 --> 00:32:38.520
It's only an eigenstate of
the annihilation operator.

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:42.100
But what sort of happens
is, the coherent state

00:32:42.100 --> 00:32:45.370
is the sum over many,
many number states with n.

00:32:45.370 --> 00:32:49.740
And the creation operator
goes from n, to n plus 1,

00:32:49.740 --> 00:32:56.680
and has matrix elements which
are square root n plus 1.

00:32:56.680 --> 00:32:59.850
So in other words,
if n is large,

00:32:59.850 --> 00:33:03.740
and if we don't care about the
subtle difference between n,

00:33:03.740 --> 00:33:08.200
and n plus 1, in this
limit the coherent state

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:12.880
is also an eigenstate of
the creation operator,

00:33:12.880 --> 00:33:18.220
with an eigenvalue,
which is beta star.

00:33:24.530 --> 00:33:28.940
This means that we have a
coherent state which is strong.

00:33:28.940 --> 00:33:31.020
Strong means, it has
a large amplitude

00:33:31.020 --> 00:33:33.370
of the electric field.

00:33:33.370 --> 00:33:36.820
The photon states which
are involved, n, are large.

00:33:36.820 --> 00:33:40.039
And we don't have whether
it be n, or n plus 1.

00:33:40.039 --> 00:33:42.080
This is actually, also,
I should mention it here,

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:44.580
explicitly-- this is
sort of the step when

00:33:44.580 --> 00:33:47.030
we have a quantum
description of light.

00:33:47.030 --> 00:33:52.630
And we replace the operators,
p and p dega, by a c number,

00:33:52.630 --> 00:33:55.150
then we really go back
to classical physics.

00:33:55.150 --> 00:33:59.210
Then we pretend that we have a
classical electric field, which

00:33:59.210 --> 00:34:05.260
is described by the
imaginary part of beta.

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:08.969
So when you have an Hamiltonian,
where you write down

00:34:08.969 --> 00:34:11.330
an electric field, and
the electric field is not

00:34:11.330 --> 00:34:14.100
changing-- you have an
external electric field.

00:34:14.100 --> 00:34:16.830
This is really the limit
of a quantum field,

00:34:16.830 --> 00:34:20.409
where you've eliminated
the operator by a c number.

00:34:20.409 --> 00:34:22.110
This is essentially
your electric field.

00:34:22.110 --> 00:34:25.320
And we do this
approximation, here.

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:30.199
Because we are interested in
the quantum features of mode

00:34:30.199 --> 00:34:33.540
a-- a is our quantum
mode, with single photons,

00:34:33.540 --> 00:34:36.719
or with a vacuum state,
and we want to squeeze it.

00:34:36.719 --> 00:34:41.090
b is just, they have
parametric drive.

00:34:41.090 --> 00:34:46.900
With this approximation, we
have only the a operators.

00:34:58.175 --> 00:34:59.050
This is our operator.

00:35:07.950 --> 00:35:09.724
Any question?

00:35:09.724 --> 00:35:12.194
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] would
give us a [INAUDIBLE], right?

00:35:16.640 --> 00:35:17.780
PROFESSOR: Yes, thank you.

00:35:17.780 --> 00:35:20.450
That means, here should
be a minus sign, yes.

00:35:27.650 --> 00:35:28.816
OK.

00:35:28.816 --> 00:35:34.440
I've motivated our discussion
with this nonlinear crystal,

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:37.900
which generates pair of photons.

00:35:37.900 --> 00:35:42.500
This is the Hamiltonian
which describes it.

00:35:42.500 --> 00:35:46.330
And if you want to have a time
evolution by this Hamiltonian,

00:35:46.330 --> 00:35:50.300
you put this Hamiltonian into
a time evolution operator.

00:35:50.300 --> 00:35:59.869
In other words, you--
e to the minus iHt

00:35:59.869 --> 00:36:00.785
is the time evolution.

00:36:05.730 --> 00:36:11.390
If you now evolve a quantum
state of light for a fixed

00:36:11.390 --> 00:36:16.890
time, t, we apply the
operator, e to the minus iHt,

00:36:16.890 --> 00:36:20.440
to the quantum state of light.

00:36:20.440 --> 00:36:26.020
What I've just said
is now the motivation

00:36:26.020 --> 00:36:31.700
for the definition of
the squeezing operator.

00:36:38.910 --> 00:36:42.620
The squeezing
operator, S of r, is

00:36:42.620 --> 00:36:52.794
defined to be the exponent
of minus r over 2,

00:36:52.794 --> 00:36:56.000
a squared minus a dega squared.

00:37:06.810 --> 00:37:10.560
This is related to
the discussion above.

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:15.820
You would say, hey, you want
to do that time evolution,

00:37:15.820 --> 00:37:17.240
where is the i?

00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:20.630
Well, I've just made
a choice of phi.

00:37:20.630 --> 00:37:31.770
If phi is chosen
to be pi over 2,

00:37:31.770 --> 00:37:33.880
then the time evolution
with the Hamiltonian,

00:37:33.880 --> 00:37:36.340
above, gives me the
squeezing operator, below.

00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:44.810
So with that motivation
we are now studying,

00:37:44.810 --> 00:37:46.745
what is the squeezing
operator doing

00:37:46.745 --> 00:37:47.890
to quantum states of light?

00:37:51.980 --> 00:37:53.950
Any questions about that?

00:37:53.950 --> 00:37:55.720
I know I spent a
lot of time on it.

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:58.930
I could have taught this
class by just saying, here

00:37:58.930 --> 00:38:01.370
is an operator, the
squeezing operator.

00:38:01.370 --> 00:38:03.120
Trust me, it does
wonderful things.

00:38:03.120 --> 00:38:05.110
And then we can
work out everything.

00:38:05.110 --> 00:38:08.530
But I find his
unsatisfying, so I

00:38:08.530 --> 00:38:11.940
wanted to show you what is
really behind this operator.

00:38:11.940 --> 00:38:14.885
And I want you to
have a feeling,

00:38:14.885 --> 00:38:17.260
where does this operator come
from, and what is it doing?

00:38:19.910 --> 00:38:24.300
In essence, what I've
introduced into our description

00:38:24.300 --> 00:38:28.270
is now an operator, which
is creating and destroying

00:38:28.270 --> 00:38:31.240
pairs of photons.

00:38:31.240 --> 00:38:33.480
And this will actually
do wonderful things

00:38:33.480 --> 00:38:35.500
to our quantum states.

00:38:46.037 --> 00:38:48.120
What are the properties
of the squeezing operator?

00:38:55.570 --> 00:38:57.516
What is important
is, it is unitary.

00:38:57.516 --> 00:38:58.890
It does a unitary
time evolution.

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:04.610
You may not see
that immediately, so

00:39:04.610 --> 00:39:08.136
let me explain that.

00:39:08.136 --> 00:39:12.190
You know from your basic
quantum mechanics course,

00:39:12.190 --> 00:39:22.660
that e to the i operator A is
unitary, when A is Hermitian.

00:39:28.230 --> 00:39:33.210
So the squeezing operator--
with the definition

00:39:33.210 --> 00:39:38.220
above-- can be written
as, I factor out

00:39:38.220 --> 00:39:48.490
2 i's over 2 a squared
minus a dega squared.

00:39:48.490 --> 00:39:54.479
And you can immediately
verify that this part, here,

00:39:54.479 --> 00:39:55.020
is Hermitian.

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:01.620
If you do the
Hermitian conjugate,

00:40:01.620 --> 00:40:03.490
a squared turns
into a dega squared.

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:06.210
a dega squared turns
into a squared.

00:40:06.210 --> 00:40:08.370
So we have a problem
with a minus sign.

00:40:08.370 --> 00:40:10.990
But if you do the
complex conjugate of i,

00:40:10.990 --> 00:40:12.720
this takes care
of the minus sign.

00:40:12.720 --> 00:40:14.490
So this part is Hermitian.

00:40:14.490 --> 00:40:17.930
We multiply it with i,
therefore this whole operator.

00:40:17.930 --> 00:40:21.140
Thus a unitary transformation
in [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:27.222 --> 00:40:27.805
Any questions?

00:40:32.770 --> 00:40:33.270
OK.

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:47.410
So after being familiar with
this operator, we want to know,

00:40:47.410 --> 00:40:50.370
what is this operator doing?

00:40:56.340 --> 00:41:00.190
I can describe, now, what this
operator does, in a Schrodinger

00:41:00.190 --> 00:41:03.400
picture, or in a
Heisenberg picture.

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:05.410
I pick whatever is
more convenient.

00:41:05.410 --> 00:41:09.920
And for now, this is
the Heisenberg picture.

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:15.740
In the Heisenberg picture, what
is changing are the operators.

00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:19.180
Therefore, in the
Heisenberg picture,

00:41:19.180 --> 00:41:25.330
this unitary transformation
transforms the operators.

00:41:25.330 --> 00:41:35.311
And we can study what happens
when we transform the operator,

00:41:35.311 --> 00:41:35.810
x.

00:41:41.710 --> 00:41:51.125
The unitary transformation
is done by-- the operator, x,

00:41:51.125 --> 00:41:54.900
is transformed by multiplying
from the left side

00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:58.610
with S, from the righthand
side with S dega.

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:11.450
You are familiar with
expressions like, this,

00:42:11.450 --> 00:42:13.600
and how to disentangle them.

00:42:18.300 --> 00:42:19.920
If you have an e to
the i alpha, e to

00:42:19.920 --> 00:42:25.430
the minus alpha, if you
could move the alpha past x.

00:42:25.430 --> 00:42:29.500
So if A and x commute,
i A, minus i A

00:42:29.500 --> 00:42:30.940
would just give unity.

00:42:30.940 --> 00:42:33.720
So therefore, this
expression is just

00:42:33.720 --> 00:42:38.830
x, unless you have non-Hermitian
commutators between A and x.

00:42:38.830 --> 00:42:43.480
I think you have solved, in
your basic mechanics course,

00:42:43.480 --> 00:42:50.680
many such problems which
involve identities of that form.

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:56.430
Then there are higher
order commutator,

00:42:56.430 --> 00:43:02.330
the commutator of A with
the commutator of a x.

00:43:05.950 --> 00:43:08.220
Unless one of those
commutator vanishes,

00:43:08.220 --> 00:43:09.725
you can get an infinite series.

00:43:23.840 --> 00:43:30.140
Our operator, A, is nothing else
than the annihilation operator,

00:43:30.140 --> 00:43:33.900
a squared minus the creation
operator, a dega squared.

00:43:33.900 --> 00:43:38.432
So we can express everything
in terms of a, and a dega.

00:43:45.370 --> 00:43:51.990
The position operator in
our harmonic oscillator

00:43:51.990 --> 00:43:54.000
can also be expressed
by a, and a dega.

00:43:58.010 --> 00:44:02.860
By doing elementary
manipulations

00:44:02.860 --> 00:44:06.110
on the righthand side,
and recouping terms,

00:44:06.110 --> 00:44:14.080
you find immediately that
the unitary transformation

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:22.620
of the Heisenberg operator, x,
gives you an x operator back.

00:44:22.620 --> 00:44:28.440
But multiplied with an
exponential, e to the r.

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:38.830
And if we would do the same to
the momentum operator, which

00:44:38.830 --> 00:44:43.130
is a minus a dega
over square root 2,

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:49.770
we will find that the unitary
transformation of the momentum

00:44:49.770 --> 00:44:56.520
operator is de-amplifying
the momentum

00:44:56.520 --> 00:44:58.660
operator by an
exponential factor.

00:45:12.260 --> 00:45:15.660
If we would assume
that we have a vacuum

00:45:15.660 --> 00:45:17.740
state in the
harmonic oscillator,

00:45:17.740 --> 00:45:22.140
and while classically, it
would be at x equals 0,

00:45:22.140 --> 00:45:24.730
p equals 0, quantum
mechanically,

00:45:24.730 --> 00:45:29.590
we have single-point noise in
x, and single-point noise in p.

00:45:29.590 --> 00:45:34.390
Then you would find that
the squeezing operator is

00:45:34.390 --> 00:45:40.900
amplifying the
quantum noise in x.

00:45:40.900 --> 00:45:46.450
But it squeezes, or
reduces, the noise in p.

00:45:54.670 --> 00:46:06.460
If we apply this squeezing
operator to the vacuum state,

00:46:06.460 --> 00:46:14.470
we obtain what is usually
called, squeezed vacuum.

00:46:25.230 --> 00:46:38.080
And it means that, in this
quasi-probability diagram,

00:46:38.080 --> 00:46:47.250
the action of the
squeezing operator

00:46:47.250 --> 00:46:52.895
is turning the vacuum
state into an ellipse.

00:47:17.980 --> 00:47:21.640
What happens to energy, here?

00:47:21.640 --> 00:47:26.810
The vacuum state is the
lowest-energy state.

00:47:26.810 --> 00:47:32.890
If you now act with a
squeezing operator to it,

00:47:32.890 --> 00:47:38.150
we obtain a state which
has-- the same energy?

00:47:38.150 --> 00:47:41.578
Is it energy-conserving,
or very high energy?

00:47:41.578 --> 00:47:43.800
AUDIENCE: Higher [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:43.800 --> 00:47:44.910
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:47:44.910 --> 00:47:45.484
Why?

00:47:45.484 --> 00:47:47.192
AUDIENCE: It's no
longer the [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:52.460 --> 00:47:53.950
PROFESSOR: Sure, yeah.

00:47:53.950 --> 00:47:55.244
It's a vacuum state.

00:47:55.244 --> 00:47:56.660
We act on the
vacuum state, but we

00:47:56.660 --> 00:47:58.660
get a state which is no
longer the vacuum state.

00:48:06.170 --> 00:48:09.970
The reason why we
have extra energy--

00:48:09.970 --> 00:48:12.950
the squeezed vacuum is
very, very energetic.

00:48:12.950 --> 00:48:19.630
Because the squeezing operator
had a dega squared, a squared.

00:48:19.630 --> 00:48:23.300
Well a squared, the annihilation
operator acting on the vacuum,

00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:24.920
gives 0.

00:48:24.920 --> 00:48:28.380
But what we are creating now,
we are acting on the vacuum,

00:48:28.380 --> 00:48:31.790
and we are creating
pairs of photons.

00:48:31.790 --> 00:48:34.430
So we are adding, literally,
energy to the system.

00:48:34.430 --> 00:48:38.240
And the energy, of course,
comes from the drive laser,

00:48:38.240 --> 00:48:42.230
from the laser 2 omega 0, which
delivers the energy in forms

00:48:42.230 --> 00:48:44.632
of photons which
are split into half,

00:48:44.632 --> 00:48:46.090
and they go into
our quantum field.

00:48:49.030 --> 00:48:51.555
In the limit of
infinite squeezing--

00:48:51.555 --> 00:48:53.270
I will show it to
you, mathematically,

00:48:53.270 --> 00:48:55.220
but it's nice to
discuss it already here.

00:48:55.220 --> 00:48:58.761
In the limit of
infinite squeezing,

00:48:58.761 --> 00:49:00.135
what is the state
we are getting?

00:49:03.630 --> 00:49:05.444
AUDIENCE: Eigenstate
of momentum.

00:49:05.444 --> 00:49:06.735
PROFESSOR: Eigenstate momentum.

00:49:09.970 --> 00:49:12.980
We get the p equals
0 eigenstate.

00:49:16.730 --> 00:49:19.175
What is the energy of the
p equals 0 eigenstate?

00:49:27.681 --> 00:49:28.647
AUDIENCE: Infinite.

00:49:28.647 --> 00:49:33.102
It has to contain
all number states.

00:49:33.102 --> 00:49:34.810
PROFESSOR: It contains
all number states?

00:49:34.810 --> 00:49:40.140
OK, you think immediately into
number states, which is great.

00:49:40.140 --> 00:49:43.100
But in a more
pedestrian way, the p

00:49:43.100 --> 00:49:46.560
equals 0 state has
no kinetic energy.

00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:50.240
But if a state is localized
in momentum, p equals 0,

00:49:50.240 --> 00:49:53.990
it has to be infinitely
smeared out on the x-axis.

00:49:53.990 --> 00:49:56.690
And don't forget, we have an
harmonic oscillator potential.

00:49:56.690 --> 00:50:00.720
If you have a particle which
is completely delocalized in x,

00:50:00.720 --> 00:50:03.850
it has infinite potential
energy at the wings.

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:06.430
So therefore in the limit
of extreme squeezing,

00:50:06.430 --> 00:50:10.249
we involve an extreme
number of number states.

00:50:10.249 --> 00:50:12.540
Actually, I want to be more
specific-- of photon pairs.

00:50:12.540 --> 00:50:17.170
We have states with 2n, and
n can be infinitely large.

00:50:17.170 --> 00:50:21.700
But we'll see in the classical
picture, what we get here

00:50:21.700 --> 00:50:24.370
when we squeeze it is,
we get the p equals

00:50:24.370 --> 00:50:28.205
0 eigenstate, which has infinite
energy, due to the harmonic

00:50:28.205 --> 00:50:29.080
oscillator potential.

00:50:34.050 --> 00:50:36.080
If we would allow
with the system

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:40.390
now, after we have squeezed
it, to evolve for a quarter

00:50:40.390 --> 00:50:42.610
period in the
harmonic oscillator,

00:50:42.610 --> 00:50:50.370
then the ellipse would turn
into an vertical ellipse.

00:50:50.370 --> 00:50:57.340
So this is now an
eigenstate of x.

00:50:57.340 --> 00:51:00.190
It's the x equals 0 eigenstate.

00:51:00.190 --> 00:51:05.560
But the x equals 0 eigenstate
has also infinite energy,

00:51:05.560 --> 00:51:08.130
because due to Heisenberg's
uncertainty relation,

00:51:08.130 --> 00:51:10.950
it involves momentum states
of infinite momentum.

00:51:15.610 --> 00:51:16.110
Questions?

00:51:33.254 --> 00:51:35.719
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] a is
the photon field, right?

00:51:35.719 --> 00:51:39.915
So p is roughly the
electrical field, right?

00:51:39.915 --> 00:51:40.540
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:51:40.540 --> 00:51:44.492
AUDIENCE: So it's kind of that
the electric field counts 0,

00:51:44.492 --> 00:51:49.760
and x is kind of the a,
the-- and it-- because of

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:51.902
[INAUDIBLE].

00:51:51.902 --> 00:51:54.866
The electrical
field is squeezed?

00:51:54.866 --> 00:51:56.348
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:51:56.348 --> 00:51:58.324
AUDIENCE: It means we
have no electrical field?

00:52:00.830 --> 00:52:03.190
PROFESSOR: We'll come
to that in a moment.

00:52:03.190 --> 00:52:07.130
I want to do a little bit
more math, to show you.

00:52:07.130 --> 00:52:10.400
I wanted to derive for you
an expression of the squeeze

00:52:10.400 --> 00:52:12.990
state, in number
basis, and such.

00:52:18.150 --> 00:52:19.610
Your question
mentioned something

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:20.776
which is absolutely correct.

00:52:20.776 --> 00:52:26.150
By squeezing that, we
have now the p-axis

00:52:26.150 --> 00:52:27.990
is the electric field axis.

00:52:27.990 --> 00:52:31.810
So now we have, actually, in
the limit of infinite squeezing,

00:52:31.810 --> 00:52:37.010
we have an electric field which
has no uncertainty anymore.

00:52:39.550 --> 00:52:45.330
By squeezing the coherent state
into a momentum eigenstate,

00:52:45.330 --> 00:52:49.630
we have created a sharp
value for the electric field.

00:52:49.630 --> 00:52:51.560
We have created an
electric field eigenstate.

00:52:54.620 --> 00:52:56.270
Well you would say,
it's pretty boring,

00:52:56.270 --> 00:52:58.650
because the only electric
field state we have created

00:52:58.650 --> 00:53:01.840
is electric field e equals 0.

00:53:01.840 --> 00:53:04.000
But in the next
half-hour, we want

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:06.640
to discuss the
displacement operator,

00:53:06.640 --> 00:53:08.000
and I will tell you what it is.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.170
That we can now
move the ellipses,

00:53:10.170 --> 00:53:13.280
and move the circles,
anywhere where we want.

00:53:13.280 --> 00:53:14.820
So once we have
an electric field

00:53:14.820 --> 00:53:18.226
state which has a sharp value
of the electric field at e

00:53:18.226 --> 00:53:22.450
equals 0, we can
just translate it.

00:53:22.450 --> 00:53:25.710
But before you get too
excited about having

00:53:25.710 --> 00:53:28.440
an eigenstate of
the electric field,

00:53:28.440 --> 00:53:30.590
I want you to think
about what happened

00:53:30.590 --> 00:53:33.920
after one quarter-period it
of the harmonic oscillator

00:53:33.920 --> 00:53:36.590
frequency.

00:53:36.590 --> 00:53:40.160
It turns upside down,
and your electric field

00:53:40.160 --> 00:53:42.880
has an infinite variance.

00:53:45.850 --> 00:53:48.470
That's what quantum
mechanics tells us.

00:53:48.470 --> 00:53:53.120
We can create
electric fields which

00:53:53.120 --> 00:53:56.640
are very precise, but
only for a short moment.

00:53:56.640 --> 00:53:59.350
So in other words, this
electric field state

00:53:59.350 --> 00:54:02.300
which we have created
would have a sharp value.

00:54:02.300 --> 00:54:04.940
A moment later, it would
be very smeared out,

00:54:04.940 --> 00:54:06.820
then it has a sharp
value again, and then

00:54:06.820 --> 00:54:09.020
it's smeared out again.

00:54:09.020 --> 00:54:12.852
I mean, that's what
squeezed states are.

00:54:12.852 --> 00:54:14.030
Other questions?

00:54:14.030 --> 00:54:15.405
AUDIENCE: That's
why [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:18.080 --> 00:54:20.530
PROFESSOR: That's why we
need homodyne detection.

00:54:20.530 --> 00:54:23.710
Yes, exactly.

00:54:23.710 --> 00:54:27.520
If we have squeezed something,
which is sort of narrow,

00:54:27.520 --> 00:54:28.870
that's great for measurement.

00:54:28.870 --> 00:54:32.190
Now we can do a
measurement of, maybe,

00:54:32.190 --> 00:54:36.086
a LIGO measurement for
gravitational waves with higher

00:54:36.086 --> 00:54:37.460
precision, because
we have a more

00:54:37.460 --> 00:54:39.900
precise value in
our quantum state.

00:54:39.900 --> 00:54:41.885
But we have to look at
it at the right time.

00:54:45.110 --> 00:54:47.510
We have to look
at it synchronized

00:54:47.510 --> 00:54:49.280
with the harmonic motion.

00:54:49.280 --> 00:54:54.290
Homodyne detection means we
look only at the sine component,

00:54:54.290 --> 00:54:55.970
or at the cosine component.

00:54:55.970 --> 00:54:58.390
Or if I want to simplify
it, what you want to do

00:54:58.390 --> 00:55:00.140
is, if you have a
state like this,

00:55:00.140 --> 00:55:02.470
you want to measure the
electric field, so to speak,

00:55:02.470 --> 00:55:03.280
stroboscopically.

00:55:03.280 --> 00:55:05.071
You want to look at
your system always when

00:55:05.071 --> 00:55:06.860
the ellipse is like this.

00:55:06.860 --> 00:55:10.240
The stroboscopic measurement
is, as I will show you,

00:55:10.240 --> 00:55:12.450
in essence, a
lock-in measurement,

00:55:12.450 --> 00:55:13.740
which is phase-sensitive.

00:55:13.740 --> 00:55:15.550
And this will be
homodyne detection.

00:55:15.550 --> 00:55:18.250
So we can only take
advantage of the squeezing,

00:55:18.250 --> 00:55:21.410
of having less uncertainty
in one quadrature component,

00:55:21.410 --> 00:55:23.924
if you do phase-sensitive
detection, which

00:55:23.924 --> 00:55:24.840
is homodyne detection.

00:55:27.470 --> 00:55:32.071
But now I'm already an
hour ahead of the course.

00:55:32.071 --> 00:55:32.570
OK.

00:55:32.570 --> 00:55:33.245
Back to basics.

00:55:43.790 --> 00:55:48.610
We want to explicitly
calculate, now,

00:55:48.610 --> 00:55:50.820
how does a squeezed
vacuum look like.

00:56:00.080 --> 00:56:03.600
We actually want to do it
twice, because it's useful.

00:56:03.600 --> 00:56:06.730
We have to see it in
two different basis.

00:56:06.730 --> 00:56:10.420
One is, I want to write down
the squeezed vacuum for you

00:56:10.420 --> 00:56:12.420
in a number representation.

00:56:12.420 --> 00:56:14.665
And then in a coherent
state representation.

00:56:19.150 --> 00:56:26.200
The squeezing operator is an
exponential function involving

00:56:26.200 --> 00:56:29.750
a squared, and a dega squared.

00:56:29.750 --> 00:56:34.610
And of course, we're now using
the Taylor expansion of that.

00:56:40.250 --> 00:56:42.475
We are acting on
the vacuum state.

00:56:45.180 --> 00:56:46.710
I will not do the calculation.

00:56:46.710 --> 00:56:47.970
It's again, elementary.

00:56:47.970 --> 00:56:54.710
You have n factorial, you have
terms with a dega acts on c,

00:56:54.710 --> 00:56:56.550
well, you pay 2 photons.

00:56:56.550 --> 00:56:59.900
If it acts again, it
adds 2 more photons,

00:56:59.900 --> 00:57:03.120
and the matrix element
of a dega acting on n

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:05.030
is square root n plus 1.

00:57:05.030 --> 00:57:07.180
You just sort of
rearrange the terms.

00:57:07.180 --> 00:57:09.280
And what you find is,
what I will write you down

00:57:09.280 --> 00:57:11.190
in the next line.

00:57:11.190 --> 00:57:13.545
The important thing you
should immediately realize

00:57:13.545 --> 00:57:17.820
is, the squeeze state is
something very special.

00:57:17.820 --> 00:57:22.140
It is the superposition
of number states,

00:57:22.140 --> 00:57:27.020
but all number states are even
because our squeezing operator

00:57:27.020 --> 00:57:28.810
creates pairs of photons.

00:57:28.810 --> 00:57:31.140
This is what the parametric
down-conversion does.

00:57:31.140 --> 00:57:33.690
We inject photons
into the vacuum,

00:57:33.690 --> 00:57:37.300
but always exactly in pairs.

00:57:37.300 --> 00:57:39.620
And therefore, it's
not a random state.

00:57:39.620 --> 00:57:42.380
It's a highly correlated state
with very special properties.

00:57:44.920 --> 00:57:45.570
OK.

00:57:45.570 --> 00:57:52.770
If you do the calculation
and recoup the terms,

00:57:52.770 --> 00:57:57.400
you get factorials,
you get 2 to the n,

00:57:57.400 --> 00:58:00.540
you get another factorial.

00:58:00.540 --> 00:58:06.840
You get hyperbolic tangent--
sorry, to the power n.

00:58:13.710 --> 00:58:22.725
And the normalization is done
by the square root of the cos

00:58:22.725 --> 00:58:23.225
function.

00:58:31.440 --> 00:58:34.640
And the more we
squeeze, the larger

00:58:34.640 --> 00:58:38.850
are the amplitudes at
higher and higher n.

00:58:38.850 --> 00:58:41.700
But this is also obvious from
the graphic representation

00:58:41.700 --> 00:58:42.610
I've shown you.

00:58:49.540 --> 00:58:53.370
Let me add the coherent
state representation.

00:59:11.480 --> 00:59:18.640
The coherence states are
related to the number

00:59:18.640 --> 00:59:25.650
states in that way.

00:59:29.300 --> 00:59:43.530
If we transform now from number
states to coherent states,

00:59:43.530 --> 00:59:47.740
the straightforward
calculation gives, now,

00:59:47.740 --> 00:59:51.520
superposition over
coherent states.

00:59:51.520 --> 00:59:57.920
Coherent states
require an integral.

00:59:57.920 --> 01:00:12.310
e to the minus e to the
r over 2, divided by--

01:00:19.800 --> 01:00:22.260
Anyway, all this
expressions, they

01:00:22.260 --> 01:00:26.800
may not be in its general
form, too illuminating.

01:00:26.800 --> 01:00:28.910
But those things can
be done analytically.

01:00:31.730 --> 01:00:34.720
I just want to mention the
interesting limiting case

01:00:34.720 --> 01:00:37.845
of infinite squeezing.

01:00:37.845 --> 01:00:39.761
AUDIENCE: When you do
the integral over alpha,

01:00:39.761 --> 01:00:41.921
is this over like, a
