01:01:46.570 --> 01:01:50.977
PROFESSOR: For negative r,
we need imaginary state.

01:01:50.977 --> 01:01:52.435
AUDIENCE: So we
should [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:59.060 --> 01:02:01.220
PROFESSOR: Let me double-check.

01:02:01.220 --> 01:02:02.260
I don't remember that.

01:02:05.570 --> 01:02:07.400
You know that,
sometimes, I admit

01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:09.870
it, the issue-- if
you research material,

01:02:09.870 --> 01:02:13.420
prepare a course some years
ago, you forget certain things.

01:02:13.420 --> 01:02:15.660
If I prepared the lecture,
and everything worked out

01:02:15.660 --> 01:02:16.868
yesterday, I would know that.

01:02:16.868 --> 01:02:19.740
But certain things
you don't remember.

01:02:19.740 --> 01:02:21.380
As far as I know,
it's the real axis.

01:02:21.380 --> 01:02:22.505
But I have to double-check.

01:02:25.786 --> 01:02:30.320
The limiting case
is interesting.

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:35.850
If r goes to infinity, you
can show that this is simply

01:02:35.850 --> 01:02:39.410
the integral, d alpha
over coherent states.

01:02:47.780 --> 01:02:57.670
We have discussed,
graphically, the situation

01:02:57.670 --> 01:03:04.100
where we had-- so these
are quasi-probabilities.

01:03:07.750 --> 01:03:13.130
In that case of
infinite squeezing,

01:03:13.130 --> 01:03:15.900
we have the momentum
eigenstate, p equals 0.

01:03:20.520 --> 01:03:27.150
This is the limit of the
infinitely squeezed vacuum,

01:03:27.150 --> 01:03:31.270
and in a coherent
state representation,

01:03:31.270 --> 01:03:37.860
it is the integral over
coherent state alpha.

01:03:37.860 --> 01:03:42.180
I'm pretty sure alpha is
real here, seeing that now.

01:03:42.180 --> 01:03:50.410
There is a second limit, which
happens simply-- you can say,

01:03:50.410 --> 01:03:54.252
by rotation, or by time
evolution-- which is the x

01:03:54.252 --> 01:03:56.700
equals 0 eigenstate.

01:03:56.700 --> 01:04:01.880
And this is proportional
to the integral over alpha

01:04:01.880 --> 01:04:05.120
when we take the
coherent state i alpha,

01:04:05.120 --> 01:04:07.370
and we integrate from
minus to plus infinity.

01:04:13.811 --> 01:04:14.310
OK.

01:04:14.310 --> 01:04:17.070
So we have connected
our squeezed states,

01:04:17.070 --> 01:04:22.285
the squeezed vacuum, with number
states, with coherent states.

01:04:26.860 --> 01:04:29.830
Now we need one more thing.

01:04:29.830 --> 01:04:33.660
So far we've only
squeezed the vacuum,

01:04:33.660 --> 01:04:37.580
and we have defined
the squeezing operator

01:04:37.580 --> 01:04:42.590
that it takes a vacuum
state and elongates it.

01:04:42.590 --> 01:04:46.210
In order to generate
more general states,

01:04:46.210 --> 01:04:48.834
we want to get away
from the origin.

01:04:48.834 --> 01:04:50.750
And this is done by the
displacement operator.

01:05:10.990 --> 01:05:16.060
The definition of the
displacement operator

01:05:16.060 --> 01:05:19.130
is given here.

01:05:19.130 --> 01:05:21.890
The displacement by
a complex number,

01:05:21.890 --> 01:05:28.620
alpha, is done by putting
alpha, and alpha star,

01:05:28.620 --> 01:05:32.110
into an exponential function.

01:05:32.110 --> 01:05:38.030
In many quantum
mechanic courses,

01:05:38.030 --> 01:05:43.380
you show very easily the
elementary properties.

01:05:43.380 --> 01:05:48.820
If the displacement
operator is used

01:05:48.820 --> 01:05:55.210
to transform the annihilation
operator, it just does that.

01:06:06.061 --> 01:06:13.067
If you take the complex
conjugate of it--

01:06:13.067 --> 01:06:14.650
so in other words,
what that means is,

01:06:14.650 --> 01:06:16.850
it's called the
displacement operator,

01:06:16.850 --> 01:06:18.790
I just take that
as the definition.

01:06:18.790 --> 01:06:21.230
But you immediately
see why it's called

01:06:21.230 --> 01:06:23.160
the displacement
operator when we

01:06:23.160 --> 01:06:26.560
do the unitary transformation
of the annihilation operator,

01:06:26.560 --> 01:06:32.140
we get the annihilation operator
displaced by a complex number.

01:06:32.140 --> 01:06:33.740
So the action,
the transformation

01:06:33.740 --> 01:06:37.750
of the annihilation operator
is the annihilator operator

01:06:37.750 --> 01:06:41.020
itself, minus a c number.

01:06:41.020 --> 01:06:44.060
So therefore, we say, the
annihilation operator data

01:06:44.060 --> 01:06:45.175
has been displaced.

01:06:47.720 --> 01:06:53.290
So this is the action of
the displacement operator

01:06:53.290 --> 01:06:57.030
on an operator-- on the
annihilation operator.

01:07:00.780 --> 01:07:03.820
The question is now, how does
the displacement operator

01:07:03.820 --> 01:07:07.160
act on quantum states?

01:07:07.160 --> 01:07:12.360
And the simplest quantum
state we want to test out

01:07:12.360 --> 01:07:14.720
is the vacuum state.

01:07:14.720 --> 01:07:19.660
And well, not surprisingly,
the displacement operator,

01:07:19.660 --> 01:07:22.320
displacing the vector
state by alpha,

01:07:22.320 --> 01:07:24.849
is creating the
coherent state, alpha.

01:07:31.840 --> 01:07:35.310
This can be proven in one line.

01:07:35.310 --> 01:07:41.950
We take our displaced
vacuum, and we act on it

01:07:41.950 --> 01:07:43.380
with the annihilation operator.

01:07:48.160 --> 01:07:53.570
If we act with the annihilation
operator on something,

01:07:53.570 --> 01:07:56.730
and we get the same thing
back times an eigenvalue,

01:07:56.730 --> 01:07:58.010
we know it's a coherent state.

01:07:58.010 --> 01:08:00.350
Because this was the
definition of coherent states.

01:08:00.350 --> 01:08:04.080
So therefore, in order to show
that this is a coherent state,

01:08:04.080 --> 01:08:08.170
we want to show that it's an
eigenstate of the annihilation

01:08:08.170 --> 01:08:09.390
operator.

01:08:09.390 --> 01:08:11.200
So this is what we want to do.

01:08:14.945 --> 01:08:18.890
The proof is very easy.

01:08:18.890 --> 01:08:24.450
By multiplying this expression
with unity, which is DD dega,

01:08:24.450 --> 01:08:26.240
we have this.

01:08:26.240 --> 01:08:29.290
And now we can use the
result for the transformation

01:08:29.290 --> 01:08:31.390
of operators.

01:08:31.390 --> 01:08:36.850
Namely, that this is simply
the annihilation operator,

01:08:36.850 --> 01:08:38.210
plus alpha.

01:08:41.529 --> 01:08:45.359
If the annihilation operator
acts on the vacuum state,

01:08:45.359 --> 01:08:46.359
we get 0.

01:08:46.359 --> 01:08:51.890
If alpha acts on the vacuum
state, we get alpha times 0.

01:08:51.890 --> 01:08:58.825
So therefore, what
we obtain is that.

01:09:03.290 --> 01:09:07.050
When the annihilation
operator acts on this state,

01:09:07.050 --> 01:09:10.590
we get alpha times the state,
and therefore the state

01:09:10.590 --> 01:09:13.130
is a coherent state
with eigenvalue alpha.

01:09:21.540 --> 01:09:26.740
In a graphical way, if
you have a vacuum state

01:09:26.740 --> 01:09:33.330
the displacement operator, D
alpha, takes a vacuum state

01:09:33.330 --> 01:09:36.451
and creates a
coherent state alpha.

01:09:50.830 --> 01:09:59.340
If you want to have squeezed
states with a finite value,

01:09:59.340 --> 01:10:03.512
well, we just discussed
the electric field.

01:10:03.512 --> 01:10:04.970
Related to the
harmonic oscillator,

01:10:04.970 --> 01:10:07.210
we want squeeze
states, which are not

01:10:07.210 --> 01:10:13.420
centered at the origin, which
have a finite value of x or p.

01:10:13.420 --> 01:10:25.510
We can now create them by
first squeezing the vacuum,

01:10:25.510 --> 01:10:26.760
and then displacing the state.

01:10:37.584 --> 01:10:39.306
AUDIENCE: What's the
physical realization

01:10:39.306 --> 01:10:42.510
of the displacement operator?

01:10:42.510 --> 01:10:44.832
PROFESSOR: What is the
physical realization

01:10:44.832 --> 01:10:46.040
of the displacement operator?

01:10:54.850 --> 01:10:57.530
Just one second.

01:10:57.530 --> 01:11:02.090
The physical representation
of the displacement operator--

01:11:02.090 --> 01:11:04.480
we'll do that on Monday--
is the following.

01:11:04.480 --> 01:11:10.250
If you pass an arbitrary state
through a beam splitter--

01:11:10.250 --> 01:11:12.780
but it's a beam splitter
which has very, very

01:11:12.780 --> 01:11:17.600
high transmission-- and then,
from the-- I'll just show that.

01:11:17.600 --> 01:11:20.900
If you have a state-- this
is a beam splitter-- which

01:11:20.900 --> 01:11:23.870
has a very high transmission,
T is approximately 1,

01:11:23.870 --> 01:11:26.130
then the state passes through.

01:11:26.130 --> 01:11:30.750
But then from the other
side of the beam splitter,

01:11:30.750 --> 01:11:33.780
you come with a very
strong coherent state.

01:11:33.780 --> 01:11:37.510
You have a coherent state
which is characterized

01:11:37.510 --> 01:11:40.210
by a large complex number, beta.

01:11:40.210 --> 01:11:44.870
And then there is a
reflection coefficient,

01:11:44.870 --> 01:11:47.620
r, which is very small.

01:11:47.620 --> 01:11:53.080
It sort of reflects the coherent
state with an amplitude r beta.

01:11:53.080 --> 01:11:56.215
If you mix together the
transmitted state and r

01:11:56.215 --> 01:11:59.030
beta-- I will show
that to you explicitly,

01:11:59.030 --> 01:12:01.750
by doing a quantum treatment
of the beam splitter--

01:12:01.750 --> 01:12:03.990
what you get is,
the initial state

01:12:03.990 --> 01:12:07.330
is pretty much transmitted
without attenuation.

01:12:07.330 --> 01:12:12.100
But the reflected part of
the strong coherent state--

01:12:12.100 --> 01:12:15.010
you compensate for the
small r by a large beta--

01:12:15.010 --> 01:12:17.540
does actually an exact
displacement of r beta.

01:12:20.270 --> 01:12:21.270
It's actually great.

01:12:21.270 --> 01:12:23.560
The beam splitter is
a wonderful device.

01:12:23.560 --> 01:12:25.460
You think you have a
displacement operator

01:12:25.460 --> 01:12:29.560
formulated with a's
and a dega's, it

01:12:29.560 --> 01:12:31.250
looks like something extract.

01:12:31.250 --> 01:12:34.610
But you can go to the lab,
simply get one beam splitter,

01:12:34.610 --> 01:12:36.610
take a strong laser
beam, and whatever

01:12:36.610 --> 01:12:38.090
you send through
the beam splitter

01:12:38.090 --> 01:12:41.390
gets displaced, gets acted
upon by the beam splitter.

01:12:44.630 --> 01:12:45.490
Yes.

01:12:45.490 --> 01:12:48.020
AUDIENCE: You showed the
displacement operator, when

01:12:48.020 --> 01:12:51.760
you acted on the vacuum state,
will displace the vacuum

01:12:51.760 --> 01:12:53.336
state to a state alpha.

01:12:53.336 --> 01:12:55.766
Does it still hold
if you acted on,

01:12:55.766 --> 01:12:57.710
like another coherent state.

01:12:57.710 --> 01:12:59.710
Or in this case, a
squeeze state like that?

01:12:59.710 --> 01:13:01.250
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:13:01.250 --> 01:13:04.280
I haven't shown it,
but it's really--

01:13:04.280 --> 01:13:08.060
it displaces-- When we
use this representation

01:13:08.060 --> 01:13:09.930
with quasi-probabilities,
it simply

01:13:09.930 --> 01:13:11.310
does a displacement
in the plane.

01:13:26.330 --> 01:13:26.830
But no.

01:13:26.830 --> 01:13:29.371
To be honest, when I say it does
a displacement on the plane,

01:13:29.371 --> 01:13:32.480
it reminds me that we
have three different ways

01:13:32.480 --> 01:13:34.420
of defining quasi-probabilities.

01:13:34.420 --> 01:13:36.805
The w, the p, and
the q representation.

01:13:39.480 --> 01:13:42.060
I know we use it all the
time, that we displace things

01:13:42.060 --> 01:13:43.130
in the plane.

01:13:43.130 --> 01:13:46.000
But I'm wondering if the
displacement operator does

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:49.045
an exact displacement of
all representations, or only

01:13:49.045 --> 01:13:51.000
of the q representation.

01:13:51.000 --> 01:13:52.625
That's something I
don't know for sure.

01:13:52.625 --> 01:13:54.875
AUDIENCE: I was thinking it
could also, like-- I mean,

01:13:54.875 --> 01:13:57.260
are you going to be able to
displace all types of light,

01:13:57.260 --> 01:14:01.033
like thermal light, or any
representation of light

01:14:01.033 --> 01:14:03.366
that you could put in, is the
same displacement operator

01:14:03.366 --> 01:14:03.949
going to work?

01:14:03.949 --> 01:14:10.850
Or is its domain just the
vacuum and coherent states?

01:14:10.850 --> 01:14:13.730
PROFESSOR: The fact is,
the coherent states--

01:14:13.730 --> 01:14:15.415
I've shown you that
it's a vacuum state.

01:14:18.310 --> 01:14:23.600
I know that's the next thing to
show, the displacement operator

01:14:23.600 --> 01:14:26.190
if you have a displacement
by alpha followed

01:14:26.190 --> 01:14:29.530
by displacement by beta,
it is equal to displacement

01:14:29.530 --> 01:14:31.090
by alpha plus beta.

01:14:31.090 --> 01:14:33.470
So displacement
operator forms a group,

01:14:33.470 --> 01:14:35.950
and if you do two
displacements, they

01:14:35.950 --> 01:14:38.310
equal into one area
of displacement,

01:14:38.310 --> 01:14:42.220
which is the sum of
two complex numbers.

01:14:42.220 --> 01:14:44.850
What I'm just saying, if you
do the first displacement

01:14:44.850 --> 01:14:47.000
you can get an arbitrarily
coherent state.

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:49.530
So therefore, the
displacement operator

01:14:49.530 --> 01:14:55.430
is exactly displacing
a coherent state

01:14:55.430 --> 01:14:58.510
by the argument of the
displacement operator.

01:14:58.510 --> 01:15:01.060
And now if you take an
arbitrary quantum state

01:15:01.060 --> 01:15:04.835
and expand it into coherent
states-- coherent states are

01:15:04.835 --> 01:15:07.319
not only complete,
they are over-complete.

01:15:07.319 --> 01:15:09.360
All you have done is,
you've done a displacement.

01:15:12.910 --> 01:15:16.216
Now the over-completeness,
of course,

01:15:16.216 --> 01:15:17.590
means you have to
think about it,

01:15:17.590 --> 01:15:21.120
because you can represent
states in more than one way

01:15:21.120 --> 01:15:22.270
by coherent states.

01:15:22.270 --> 01:15:24.030
But if you have
your representation,

01:15:24.030 --> 01:15:25.831
you just displace
it, and this is

01:15:25.831 --> 01:15:27.497
the result of the
displacement operator.

01:15:32.170 --> 01:15:36.910
So since the q
representation is simply,

01:15:36.910 --> 01:15:38.520
you take the
statistical operator

01:15:38.520 --> 01:15:41.480
and look for the
elements in alpha,

01:15:41.480 --> 01:15:43.780
and if you displace alpha,
the q representation

01:15:43.780 --> 01:15:44.730
has been moved around.

01:15:44.730 --> 01:15:47.590
So I'm sure that for
the q representation,

01:15:47.590 --> 01:15:52.720
for the q quasi-probabilities,
the displacement operator

01:15:52.720 --> 01:15:54.840
shifted around in this place.

01:15:54.840 --> 01:16:00.685
For the w and p
representation, I'm not sure.

01:16:00.685 --> 01:16:02.310
Maybe there's an
expert in the audience

01:16:02.310 --> 01:16:06.830
who knows more
about it than I do.

01:16:06.830 --> 01:16:08.840
OK.

01:16:08.840 --> 01:16:10.520
We have just five minutes left.

01:16:15.610 --> 01:16:18.410
I want to discuss now
the electric field

01:16:18.410 --> 01:16:20.720
of squeezed states.

01:16:20.720 --> 01:16:25.840
And for that, let
me load a picture.

01:16:33.220 --> 01:16:34.145
Insert picture.

01:16:40.200 --> 01:16:40.870
Classroom files.

01:16:55.420 --> 01:17:02.561
Let us discuss, now, the
electric field of squeezed

01:17:02.561 --> 01:17:03.060
states.

01:17:18.010 --> 01:17:23.380
Just as a reminder, we can
discuss the electric field

01:17:23.380 --> 01:17:27.740
by using the quasi-probability
representation.

01:17:27.740 --> 01:17:30.880
And the electric field
is the projection

01:17:30.880 --> 01:17:33.225
of the quasi-probabilities
on the vertical axis.

01:17:36.150 --> 01:17:40.000
And then the time evolution
is, that everything rotates

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:42.880
with omega in this
complex plane.

01:17:50.520 --> 01:17:51.900
We discussed it already.

01:17:51.900 --> 01:17:56.700
For coherent state, we have
a circle which rotates.

01:17:56.700 --> 01:18:00.220
Therefore, the projected
fuzziness of the electric field

01:18:00.220 --> 01:18:01.710
is always the same.

01:18:01.710 --> 01:18:05.400
And as time goes by, we have
a sinusoidal-bearing electric

01:18:05.400 --> 01:18:07.972
field.

01:18:07.972 --> 01:18:09.180
Let me just make one comment.

01:18:09.180 --> 01:18:13.450
If you look into the literature,
some people actually say,

01:18:13.450 --> 01:18:15.760
the electric field
is the projection

01:18:15.760 --> 01:18:17.420
on the horizontal axis.

01:18:17.420 --> 01:18:21.240
So there are people who say,
the electric field is given

01:18:21.240 --> 01:18:25.285
by the x-coordinate of
the harmonic oscillator,

01:18:25.285 --> 01:18:28.220
whereas I'm telling you,
it's the p-coordinate.

01:18:28.220 --> 01:18:30.450
Well, if you think
one person is wrong,

01:18:30.450 --> 01:18:33.330
I would suggest you just
wait a quarter-period

01:18:33.330 --> 01:18:36.320
of the harmonic oscillator, and
then the other person is right.

01:18:36.320 --> 01:18:38.320
It's really just a
phase convention.

01:18:38.320 --> 01:18:41.560
What do you assume
to be t equals

01:18:41.560 --> 01:18:44.385
0-- it's really arbitrary.

01:18:44.385 --> 01:18:46.510
But here in this course,
I will use the projections

01:18:46.510 --> 01:18:48.451
on the vertical axis.

01:18:48.451 --> 01:18:48.950
OK.

01:18:48.950 --> 01:18:53.320
If you project the number
state, we get always,

01:18:53.320 --> 01:18:56.302
0 electric field, with
a large uncertainty.

01:18:56.302 --> 01:18:57.385
So that's just a reminder.

01:19:01.920 --> 01:19:05.200
But now we have
a squeezed state.

01:19:05.200 --> 01:19:09.430
It's a displaced squeezed state.

01:19:09.430 --> 01:19:12.740
If you project it
onto the y-axis,

01:19:12.740 --> 01:19:17.070
we have first some
large uncertainty.

01:19:17.070 --> 01:19:20.830
I think this plot assumes that
we rotate with negative time,

01:19:20.830 --> 01:19:24.020
so I apologize for that.

01:19:24.020 --> 01:19:26.080
You can just invert
time, if you want.

01:19:26.080 --> 01:19:30.670
So after a quarter-period,
the ellipse is now horizontal,

01:19:30.670 --> 01:19:34.690
and that means the electric
field is very sharp.

01:19:34.690 --> 01:19:37.680
As time goes by, you
see that the uncertainty

01:19:37.680 --> 01:19:40.040
of the electric field
is large, small, large,

01:19:40.040 --> 01:19:41.140
small-- it modulates.

01:19:46.470 --> 01:19:49.930
It can become very extreme,
when you do extreme squeezing,

01:19:49.930 --> 01:19:53.050
so you have an extremely precise
value of the electric field,

01:19:53.050 --> 01:19:57.360
here, but you've a large
uncertainty, there.

01:19:57.360 --> 01:20:00.540
Sometimes you want
to accurately measure

01:20:00.540 --> 01:20:02.560
the 0 crossing of
the electric field.

01:20:02.560 --> 01:20:05.240
This may be something
which interests you,

01:20:05.240 --> 01:20:06.870
for an experiment.

01:20:06.870 --> 01:20:10.750
In that case, you
actually want to have

01:20:10.750 --> 01:20:13.480
an ellipse which is
horizontally squeezed.

01:20:13.480 --> 01:20:16.130
Now, whenever the
electric field is 0,

01:20:16.130 --> 01:20:17.740
there is very little noise.

01:20:17.740 --> 01:20:20.590
But after a quarter-period,
when the electric field

01:20:20.590 --> 01:20:23.220
reaches its maximum,
you have a lot of noise.

01:20:23.220 --> 01:20:27.330
So it's sort of your choice
which way you squeeze.

01:20:27.330 --> 01:20:32.310
Whether you want the
electric field to be precise,

01:20:32.310 --> 01:20:35.835
have little fluctuations
when it goes through 0,

